WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.280
My name is Melissa Van Bussel, and I'm an analyst at Statistics Canada, which is the

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:15.080
official statistical agency of Canada.

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:21.080
Today, I'll be talking about how my team converted our documentation to Quarto, and

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:25.240
doing this conversion was definitely a journey.

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:28.600
Not all journeys go according to plan.

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:33.240
But before I get into the details of how we did this conversion, I want to first start

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:39.439
by sharing a story about another journey that didn't go according to plan.

00:00:39.439 --> 00:00:44.880
I want to take you all back to the DIY era of the COVID-19 pandemic.

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:50.160
During that time, my housemate and I decided to build our own outdoor couch.

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:54.799
We found this template online, which looked doable.

00:00:54.799 --> 00:01:00.119
We bought the wood from the blueprint and coughed up the $85 Home Depot delivery fee

00:01:00.119 --> 00:01:04.279
because we didn't have a car that would fit the wood in it.

00:01:04.279 --> 00:01:09.320
But as soon as we got the wood delivered, we quickly realized that the saw we had wasn't

00:01:09.320 --> 00:01:16.480
exactly going to cut it.

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:20.400
So we needed to borrow a better saw from a family friend.

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:27.599
This made everything so much more efficient, and we managed to finish building the couch.

00:01:27.599 --> 00:01:31.360
Or so we thought.

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:36.519
It turns out that the instructions that we'd been following were actually only for the

00:01:36.519 --> 00:01:39.199
part of the couch that was missing an arm.

00:01:39.199 --> 00:01:44.940
We had only purchased half of the wood that we needed.

00:01:44.980 --> 00:01:50.820
So we needed to head back to Home Depot, and we bought the rest of the wood that we needed.

00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:53.739
There was just one problem left.

00:01:53.739 --> 00:01:57.139
We still didn't have a car that would fit all the wood in it.

00:01:57.139 --> 00:02:01.860
And we had paid that $85 delivery fee the first time, but we really didn't want to pay

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:04.660
that again.

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:11.059
So we borrowed a truck from a friend in order to get the rest of the wood home.

00:02:11.059 --> 00:02:16.619
Once we had the right tools and all the resources and help that we needed, we were able to successfully

00:02:16.619 --> 00:02:20.339
finish building the couch.

00:02:20.339 --> 00:02:25.899
This journey full of unexpected challenges is very similar to the journey that my team

00:02:25.899 --> 00:02:29.699
had when converting our documentation to Cordo.

00:02:29.699 --> 00:02:34.660
Today, I'll share that journey with you, as well as the challenges that we faced along

00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:35.660
the way.

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:40.860
I'll also share some tips and tricks that we used, all of which are applicable to any

00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:44.740
kind of Cordo project.

00:02:44.740 --> 00:02:49.419
I'm going to start by providing some necessary context.

00:02:49.419 --> 00:02:54.539
I work on a team at Statistics Canada that publishes statistics related to education

00:02:54.539 --> 00:02:56.580
in Canada.

00:02:56.580 --> 00:03:01.660
There's a lot of domain knowledge and subject matter, as well as methodological concepts

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:05.720
that need to be documented somewhere.

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:11.179
This leads to a very important distinction in the title of my talk.

00:03:11.179 --> 00:03:17.860
When I say the word documentation, I'm not talking about our package documentation.

00:03:17.860 --> 00:03:22.020
I'm talking about documentation that defines terms like these.

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:28.360
So it's really the subject matter documentation and not the package documentation.

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:34.240
I'm talking about the sort of information that somebody might put in a wiki or on Confluence

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:37.839
or something like that.

00:03:37.839 --> 00:03:41.759
Whatever you call yours, we call ours a user guide.

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:48.160
And for us, it was previously stored as a 120-page Word document.

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:53.720
Scrolling through this document was slow, and only one person could edit it at a time,

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:58.699
which was a significant challenge for our large team.

00:03:58.699 --> 00:04:03.940
Our version control was limited to the track changes feature in Word, which made it pretty

00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:09.300
challenging to follow updates over time.

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:14.119
After last year's conference, we discovered Cordo, which would address those challenges

00:04:14.119 --> 00:04:17.760
that we had been facing with Word.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:23.500
When we started this conversion, though, we were all total beginners with Cordo.

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:28.779
This meant that in order for us to effectively complete this task, we would need to use the

00:04:28.779 --> 00:04:31.279
right tools.

00:04:31.279 --> 00:04:35.160
When you're working with Cordo, there are so many tools that you can use to make your

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:38.760
life easier.

00:04:38.760 --> 00:04:46.720
If you're looking to convert existing text to Cordo, a good first step is to convert

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:52.839
the text to Markdown first if it's not already in that format.

00:04:52.839 --> 00:04:58.399
We used the Pandoc convert function from the R Markdown package to automatically convert

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:03.320
our Word document from Word format to Markdown.

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:07.679
This provided us a really great starting point.

00:05:07.679 --> 00:05:12.679
Although this was a great starting point, it was still just a starting point.

00:05:12.679 --> 00:05:17.119
There was still a lot of formatting changes that we needed to make.

00:05:17.119 --> 00:05:21.920
In order to make this part of the job easier, we set up custom keyboard shortcuts in our

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:23.799
IDEs.

00:05:23.799 --> 00:05:29.720
For example, we set up a shortcut that made it a little bit easier to convert URLs into

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:32.559
valid Markdown links.

00:05:32.559 --> 00:05:39.000
If you're using RStudio as your IDE, you can also set up code snippets, which are a great

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:47.839
way to automate code insertion for anything that you find yourself typing out very frequently.

00:05:47.839 --> 00:05:52.720
This is great for when you want to use some of the cool Cordo features that take a little

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:57.079
bit longer to type out.

00:05:57.079 --> 00:06:02.359
I really recommend checking out Tom Mock's GitHub gist that contains code snippets that

00:06:02.359 --> 00:06:05.220
are very useful for working with Cordo.

00:06:05.220 --> 00:06:11.519
Those code snippets are provided for both RStudio and VS Code.

00:06:11.519 --> 00:06:17.380
For any syntax that's a little bit trickier to type out, there are ways to avoid doing

00:06:17.380 --> 00:06:19.279
things manually.

00:06:19.359 --> 00:06:26.119
Personally, I find the syntax for Markdown tables to be extremely finicky.

00:06:26.119 --> 00:06:31.519
RStudio's Visual Editor comes in great handy for this, or you can also find similar tools

00:06:31.519 --> 00:06:37.600
online if you're using different IDEs.

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:42.279
For situations like these, Generative AI is another great option.

00:06:42.279 --> 00:06:49.260
Both ChatGPT and GitHub Copilot have a pretty decent knowledge of Cordo syntax, but an even

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:53.940
better understanding of HTML and CSS.

00:06:53.940 --> 00:06:58.739
You can use Generative AI for a variety of use cases, but you'll find it particularly

00:06:58.739 --> 00:07:04.299
helpful for making your Cordo projects more aesthetic.

00:07:04.299 --> 00:07:08.700
If you're looking to use these tools, I've got a video on my YouTube channel that explains

00:07:08.700 --> 00:07:17.619
how to use ChatGPT and GitHub Copilot as an R programmer.

00:07:17.619 --> 00:07:21.260
Once you're done with creating the content, there's something that you can do to make

00:07:21.260 --> 00:07:24.260
maintaining the content easier as well.

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:29.500
You can use Git for proper version control, and you can use either GitHub Actions or GitLab

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:34.540
Pipelines to automate the publishing of your content.

00:07:34.540 --> 00:07:39.899
This will make it so that every single time you make a commit using Git, the published

00:07:39.899 --> 00:07:47.059
version of your content will be automatically updated without you having to do anything.

00:07:47.059 --> 00:07:51.980
I promise that this is much easier than it sounds, and I've got videos on my YouTube

00:07:51.980 --> 00:08:00.299
channel that give examples of Cordo pipelines using both GitHub Actions and GitLab Pipelines.

00:08:00.299 --> 00:08:05.220
Or if you prefer to avoid the whole pipeline thing altogether, and you're just looking

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:10.179
for somewhere to host your Cordo content for free, I've also got a video that explains

00:08:10.179 --> 00:08:17.500
how to use Cordo Pub to publish a website in under a minute.

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:22.420
There are so many great tools for working with Cordo, but there are probably still going

00:08:22.420 --> 00:08:26.579
to be some times when you need a little bit of extra help.

00:08:26.579 --> 00:08:30.420
There's probably going to come a point where you want to do something and you don't know

00:08:30.420 --> 00:08:32.780
how to do that thing.

00:08:32.780 --> 00:08:38.780
Whenever that happens, you can ask the R community for help.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:43.099
When it comes to asking Cordo questions, there's an order of operations that I like

00:08:43.099 --> 00:08:44.940
to follow.

00:08:44.940 --> 00:08:49.859
Of course, you should always start by checking the Cordo documentation and googling your

00:08:49.859 --> 00:08:55.960
problem to see if somebody's already made a video, a blog post, or posted on Stack Overflow

00:08:55.960 --> 00:08:58.539
about it.

00:08:58.539 --> 00:09:02.179
But if you can't find what you're looking for there, you can also reach out to your

00:09:02.179 --> 00:09:07.219
colleagues or friends, including the ones you make while here at Conf.

00:09:07.219 --> 00:09:12.179
You can also reach out to your local R user group or your R-Ladies chapter, if you have

00:09:12.179 --> 00:09:13.179
one.

00:09:13.179 --> 00:09:19.359
In fact, if there's anyone in the audience from Ottawa, the R-Ladies Ottawa chapter will

00:09:19.359 --> 00:09:27.340
be having our first event in three years, coming up next Tuesday, September 26th.

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:33.640
In our case last summer, though, we were among the first to be using Cordo in our area, which

00:09:33.640 --> 00:09:39.799
meant that we sometimes needed to seek help using other avenues.

00:09:39.799 --> 00:09:47.039
Twitter is a great place for this, especially if you use the hashtags RStats and CordoPub.

00:09:47.039 --> 00:09:53.760
For example, I tweeted this, asking if there's a clever way to render Cordo documents to

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:59.400
PDF if the HTML version contains GIFs.

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:03.599
Within an hour, someone had responded to my question, explaining that there's a way to

00:10:03.599 --> 00:10:13.840
make content visible or invisible, depending on the format of the output.

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:19.159
Another great place that you can ask your Cordo questions is by using the Q&A feature

00:10:19.159 --> 00:10:25.580
on the discussions portion of the Cordo CLI GitHub repo.

00:10:25.580 --> 00:10:31.059
This is where the development for Cordo happens, and when you post a question in the Q&A here,

00:10:31.059 --> 00:10:35.900
it might be answered by a member of the R community, or maybe even a member of the Cordo

00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:38.619
development team itself.

00:10:38.619 --> 00:10:45.539
Personally, I've found the Q&A feature to be an incredible resource.

00:10:45.539 --> 00:10:50.859
There's been times where I've been stumped on syntax for multiple days, and I feel just

00:10:50.859 --> 00:10:53.760
about ready to give up.

00:10:53.760 --> 00:11:01.960
But then I post the question on the Q&A, and I'm able to get an answer within the same day.

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:08.140
For example, we needed to create a bilingual Cordo website that would allow the user to

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:12.119
switch between English and French.

00:11:12.119 --> 00:11:18.000
To do this, we created a Cordo project that had an English folder and a French folder

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.719
with identical file structure.

00:11:21.719 --> 00:11:27.159
Using the Cordo documentation, we were able to find a way to create a toggle that would

00:11:27.159 --> 00:11:31.400
allow the user to switch between the two languages.

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:36.400
The only problem was that when the user would click the button, it would take them back

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:43.299
to the home page rather than displaying the current page in the opposite language.

00:11:43.299 --> 00:11:50.640
We asked about this in the Cordo Q&A, and it was suggested that we use JavaScript to

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:56.679
create a button that would modify the URL when clicked.

00:11:56.679 --> 00:12:02.320
After following an example that was provided in the comments of that Q&A, we were able

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:12.719
to successfully create this button, and we now have a fully bilingual Cordo website.

00:12:12.719 --> 00:12:20.119
As you become more and more advanced with Cordo, you might find yourself asking questions

00:12:20.119 --> 00:12:23.840
that are actually unanswerable.

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:28.679
What I mean by that is that there might be features that you're looking for that aren't

00:12:28.679 --> 00:12:32.340
currently implemented in Cordo.

00:12:32.340 --> 00:12:37.080
After all, it is still pretty new.

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:42.520
If this is the case, there's a good chance that someone from the Cordo development team

00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:48.599
will comment on your Q&A indicating that this is the case, or they might suggest a clever

00:12:48.599 --> 00:12:52.200
workaround instead.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:56.000
You can also check to see if there's already been a feature request for whatever you're

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.719
trying to do, and if not, you can create one yourself.

00:13:00.719 --> 00:13:06.679
Personally, I find this to be one of the coolest things about using Cordo, especially at this

00:13:06.679 --> 00:13:09.020
point in time.

00:13:09.020 --> 00:13:14.380
Even as an end user of Cordo, you could have the opportunity to help shape the future of

00:13:14.380 --> 00:13:18.739
Cordo.

00:13:18.739 --> 00:13:24.260
Once we had a working first draft, it was time to share our project more broadly with

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:26.340
others.

00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:30.940
This is where we faced our third challenge, and where you're likely to face a challenge

00:13:30.940 --> 00:13:32.419
too.

00:13:32.419 --> 00:13:37.979
Although you might be super passionate about Cordo and confident in its potential, it is

00:13:37.979 --> 00:13:45.780
still a pretty new product, and not everyone is going to be on board on day one.

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:52.179
Getting that support for Cordo can be challenging, and the approach that you take may differ

00:13:52.179 --> 00:13:56.260
depending on your target audience.

00:13:56.260 --> 00:14:01.380
With management, a good strategy is to show, not tell.

00:14:01.380 --> 00:14:07.820
Rather than starting a conversation about Cordo, create a cool project using Cordo that

00:14:07.820 --> 00:14:10.400
will wow people.

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:15.979
When someone inevitably asks you how you made it, this is when you can talk about what Cordo

00:14:15.979 --> 00:14:19.380
is.

00:14:19.380 --> 00:14:23.900
Depending on your workplace, you may have the additional challenge of Cordo not currently

00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:27.619
being on the list of installable software.

00:14:27.619 --> 00:14:33.460
In our case last summer, we didn't have access to a version of RStudio that came prepackaged

00:14:33.460 --> 00:14:34.859
with Cordo.

00:14:34.900 --> 00:14:41.179
Instead, we needed to use VS Code as our editor while we waited for our version of RStudio

00:14:41.179 --> 00:14:44.299
to be updated.

00:14:44.299 --> 00:14:49.299
Another option is to use Rocker, which is a Docker image that comes prepackaged with

00:14:49.299 --> 00:14:51.979
Cordo.

00:14:51.979 --> 00:14:56.539
In order to get your colleagues on board with Cordo, I highly suggest creating templates

00:14:56.539 --> 00:15:01.739
that you or anyone else can use as a starting point for their project.

00:15:01.739 --> 00:15:05.820
Not only is this going to prevent you from needing to reinvent the wheel every time,

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:09.979
but it'll also reduce the barriers that others might face when trying to learn a new

00:15:09.979 --> 00:15:12.219
tool.

00:15:12.219 --> 00:15:17.099
You can either start with a pre-existing template, for example from the awesome Cordo repo on

00:15:17.099 --> 00:15:20.460
GitHub, or you can create your own.

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:27.419
For example, I created this Statistics Canada theme for the Reveal.js format.

00:15:27.419 --> 00:15:32.380
For any colleagues who don't have Git or Markdown experience, a great way to enable

00:15:32.380 --> 00:15:40.059
collaboration is to use the report issue feature on your Cordo projects.

00:15:40.059 --> 00:15:45.099
With just a single click of a button, a new issue can be created on the project's GitLab

00:15:45.099 --> 00:15:51.700
or GitHub repo, and the necessary changes can be described in plain text using a what-you-see-is-what-you-get

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:53.799
type of text editor.

00:15:53.799 --> 00:15:59.979
This then makes it very easy for the developer to go in and copy-paste the modifications

00:15:59.979 --> 00:16:06.640
that need to be made with little to no modification on their end, allowing for effective collaboration

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:09.200
across the board.

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:14.799
And finally, you can also enable Word and PDF formats for any end users who might prefer

00:16:14.799 --> 00:16:20.000
those formats over HTML.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:24.880
Once we had the right tools and all of the resources and help that we needed, we were

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:31.119
able to successfully convert our user guide from Word to Cordo, and we now have documentation

00:16:31.119 --> 00:16:34.760
that feels amazing to developers and users alike.

00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:41.880
Eric, who's a developer, appreciates how easy it is to automatically generate our documentation

00:16:41.880 --> 00:16:45.599
in three different formats using just a single commit.

00:16:45.599 --> 00:16:51.719
And Sylvie, who's an end user of the documentation, appreciates that Cordo websites are easy and

00:16:51.719 --> 00:16:59.520
pleasant to use, and that creating an issue whenever there are typos is straightforward.

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:04.099
At Statistics Canada more broadly, Cordo is now a pretty popular tool.

00:17:04.099 --> 00:17:08.920
Not only has my team continued to use it for any new projects that we start, but other

00:17:08.920 --> 00:17:11.760
teams have started to adopt it as well.

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:18.719
For example, the website for Statistics Canada's R and Python User Group, or RPUG for short,

00:17:18.719 --> 00:17:22.800
was recently converted from Hugo to Cordo.

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:27.400
Training resources for teaching people about R and Databricks have also been created using

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:32.959
Cordo, and at the individual level, analysts have started using the reveal.js format to

00:17:32.959 --> 00:17:37.680
create stunning presentations.

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:42.880
I hope that with these tips and tricks, you're able to have a successful project, whether

00:17:42.880 --> 00:17:46.160
that's adopting Cordo or completing your own DIY.

00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:47.280
Thank you.

